title: For Sale:  M1895 Dutch Mannlicher
postcontent: I'm looking to sell my M1895 Dutch Mannlicher made in 1918 at the Hembrug Factory in Luxembourg. It was originally chambered in 6.5x53r, but sometime during it's life, it was rechambered in .303 British. It was made for the Dutch Home Army in 1918, and served with them until it was sent to the Dutch East Indies to be used to arm the indigenous forces and what was left of the Dutch Army in the Pacific Colonies. This rifle doesn't have an import mark so one can speculate how it came into the country. It could have come into the country before 1968 when import marks were required, or brought home by a GI who served in the Pacific, but there's no proof of the latter. I have not fired it, but the bore is clean. Free of pitting, rust, and debris. The rifling is strong for it's age. The wood is beat up, gouged, dinged, scratched, and chipped, but it can be fired safely. It has seen some hard use in its life. The finish above the wood line is rust free, it just has the normal patina for being in the Pacific theater. Below the wood line is a mystery, I can see some pitting, but that is normal, and will not hinder the functionality of the rifle. I cannot get the action screws loose, even after two days of being soaked in Aero Kroil, and it looks as if someone before me has tried to get them loose as well and they began to booger up the screws but they're not destroyed. The action is surprisingly smooth, I wish all my rifles were this smooth! It can be fired, but only in single shot, for it takes a Mannlicher style stripper clip that isn't for the .303 British round. This is a unique, and hard to find rifle. Feel free to ask any questions and I am happy to send specific pictures. Email me, or text me at 256-43one-42five7. I'm asking $400 OBO for this rifle. Again, this is a uncommon rifle. It has some grease and dirt around it, and I didn't remove it due to it giving the rifle character and showing some of its former life. You probably will never see one of these again! I am a Curio and Relic License holder, so I can ship and sell to others in other states, but no sales to NY, NJ, CA, CO, MD, Cook County, Il, and where prohibited.

postcontent:
I've taken the Tavor to the range twice and have about 100 rounds through it.  It's an awesome rifle and I hate to give it up, but I'd like to put the funds toward a high-end 1911 (got the bug), an ACOG for my AR, or maybe an M&P 9 CORE with an RMR.

This is the IDF model which is exactly the same as what is issued to the Israeli Defense Forces except it's semi-auto instead of full-auto.  It includes an integrated Mepro 21 reflex sight with a triangle reticle lit by fiber optics (during the day) & tritium (at night).  The sight itself sells for $475-500, so $1800 is an absolute steal for this rifle.

Check out the details at the IWI website: http://www.iwi.us/TAVOR/TAVOR-TSIDF16

It's in perfect condition (basically new) and comes with everything that came from the factory, including the original box, manuals, unused IWI 30-round magazine, and unused cleaning kit - have plenty of cleaning supplies so didn't even open this one.

I'm not desperate for the cash, not really interested in trades, and won't take less than $1800.  Even at that price, I'm seriously thinking about just keeping it and enjoying it for a few years!  With ammo prices back to reasonable prices, I could have a lot of fun with it without breaking the bank.  I live in Holly Springs, but will make the transfer at Fuquay Gun & Gold (where I bought it).

title: For Sale/Trade:  FS/FT - UTAS-15 Tactical 12 w/center mass laser
postcontent:
I've got a late generation UTAS-15 tactical shotgun 14+1 with Laserlyte Kryptonite Center-Mass laser, vertical grip on pump rail and nice camo range bag and if wanted 1x Sightmark Hoohraphic sight w/built in laser.  Likely overkill with the Laserlyte but a good cheap addition for any other rail.  You can purchase the built in Flash/Laser units from Rockwell for $219 as well.  UTAS built in the selector switch but gave the option for add-on before or after purchase.  I've  got an email into Rockwell for written proof of its DOB however verified this from the original owner and a Rockwell rep as well.  This is also evident by the magnesium and other later additions which are present throughout the shotgun.  Early reviews weren't real good for the UTAS back about 8 years ago however as of 2012 they've turned a wicked looking shotgun into a wicked performing shotgun as well.  This has been verified by a range test at my local ShootSmart performing various quick fire tests (range allowed) except the 360 angle fire.  I personally wasn't comfortable shooting upside down in an indoor range.  :)

If you have any spec questions feel free to ask or simply Google it.  Other than the early versions they really don't have any differences as UTAS makes required changes as they go so no such thing as "revisions".  I'm not much of a shotgun guy only preferring one near by for home defense if necessary.  The UTAS however takes "home defense" to a whole new level.  Being more into hand guns and Tactical long guns I'm looking more for a trade than anything however I'll entertain any decent offer.  The worst either party can say is "no".  I'm in no hurry to offload so please keep it respectful and I promise to do the same.  I'm open to cash+trade or trade+cash from my end if needed etc.  I enjoy owning and shooting guns and trading is about the best way to accomplish this without going broke.  Have a great day!

$850 w/o laser, $900 with

Preference will be given to anyone with the following:

Kimber, Rock Island 1911 (subcompact preferred), any quality AR or AK, Benelli M4, higher end revolver, Desert Eagle

title: For Sale:  Taurus Slim 709 9mm
location: NW San Antonio, San Antonio, Texas
postcontent:
Light (19 oz) and easy to conceal carry.   Doesn't jam and extremely accurate

Great Pro Trigger System allows for DA/SA Double Action/Single Action. If you don't know what that means. I'll try to explain.  When you shoot double action (picture a revolver's hammer), as you squeeze the trigger, the hammer moves backwards to a point (one action), then when it reaches that point, it slams forward (second action of the Double action) onto the bullet or a fireing pin which then hits the bullet. Trouble is, as you're squeezing to make the hammer go back, you're also moving your aim around the target. When it finally slams forward, you are sometimes off the target.  That's why many people miss or shoot poorly. Now, Single Action is when the hammer is already pulled back and the next slight squeeze of the trigger makes it slam forward and the bullet goes off. If you were on your target, you will probably hit your target.  People around you say "Wow!".  Well, maybe not, but it is more fun to shoot well, than not.

You must be legal to buy a gun in Texas and you must have a Texas ID.
